<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-07-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-07-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="278" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d278">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">816.24/705</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chief of the Division of the American
                                Republics</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bonsal</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Assistant Chief of
                                the Division</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>], <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-07-09">July 9, 1943</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Cabot</hi>: Commander Parker spoke to me this
                            morning about the interest of the Salvadoran Military Attaché, whose
                            name, I believe, is Baroń, in obtaining 1,000 submachine guns. May I
                            have your views <pb facs="0323" n="309" xml:id="pg_309"/> on this? It
                            seems to me to be a rather considerable order of an article which has
                            played a sinister role in Central America.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Philip W. Bonsal</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>